Month = {{SEP 25}},
Abstract = {{Background: Previous studies have reported that patients with bipolar
   disorder (BPD) exhibit altered emotional processing and regulation.
   However, results remain largely inconsistent across studies. The aim of
   the current study was to further examine affective processing in
   patients with bipolar disorder.
   Methods: Twenty-three patients diagnosed with BPD (Type I) and 18
   healthy matched controls completed a backward-masked affect paradigm
   while undergoing functional magnetic resonance imaging. Participants
   also completed a computerized, overt task of facial emotional
   discrimination after scanning.
   Results: Results demonstrated altered affective processing of happy and
   fearful stimuli in bipolar participants in the amygdala, anterior
   cingulate cortex (ACC), and dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC)
   relative to controls. BPD participants also displayed significant
   deficits in identifying fearful facial affect.
   Limitations: This study has a moderate sample size, and the patients
   with BPD were significantly older than the healthy control participants;
   this did not appear to impact results, and although statistically
   significant, it is not likely biologically significant.
   Conclusions: These findings may have implications for patients with BPD,
   as altered affective processing could result in deficits in reading
   social cues. (C) 2013 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.}},
