Abstract = {{This functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) research explores how
   observers make causal beliefs about an event in terms of the person or
   situation. Thirty-four participants read various short descriptions of
   social events that implied either the person or the situation as the
   cause. Half of them were explicitly instructed to judge whether the
   event was caused by something about the person or the situation
   (intentional inferences), whereas the other half was instructed simply
   to read the material carefully (spontaneous inferences). The results
   showed common activation in areas related to mentalizing, across all
   types of causes or instructions (posterior superior temporal sulcus,
   temporo-parietal junction, precuneus). However, the medial prefrontal
   cortex was activated only under spontaneous instructions, but not under
   intentional instruction. This suggests a bias toward person attributions
   (e.g. fundamental attribution bias). Complementary to this, intentional
   situation attributions activated a stronger and more extended network
   compared to intentional person attributions, suggesting that situation
   attributions require more controlled, extended and broader processing of
