Number = {{5}},
Pages = {{546-555}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{Although neuroimaging studies strongly implicate the medial prefrontal
   cortex (ventral and dorsal), cingulate gyrus (anterior and posterior),
   precuneus and temporoparietal cortex in mediating self-referential
   processing (SRP), little is known about the neural bases mediating
   individual differences in valenced SRP, that is, processes intrinsic to
   self-esteem. This study investigated the neural correlates of
   experimentally engendered valenced SRP via the Visual-Verbal Self-Other
   Referential Processing Task in 20 women with fMRI. Participants viewed
   pictures of themselves or unknown other women during separate trials
   while covertly rehearsing `I am' or `She is', followed by reading
   valenced trait adjectives, thus variably associating the self/other with
   positivity/negativity. Response within dorsal and ventral medial
   prefrontal cortex, cingulate cortex and left temporoparietal cortex
   varied with individual differences in both pre-task rated
   self-descriptiveness of the words, as well as task-induced affective
   responses. Results are discussed as they relate to a social cognitive
   and affective neuroscience view of self-esteem.}},
